# Task: Style Lists

## What
Apply custom styling to unordered and ordered lists with neon green accents.

## Why
- Lists are used extensively (skills, deliverables, etc.)
- Custom bullets reinforce the theme
- Proper spacing improves readability
- Default bullets are boring

## Design Specification

### Unordered Lists
- Custom bullet: Neon green
- Options: `•` character, `>` character, or CSS ::marker
- Adequate line-height and margin between items

### Ordered Lists
- Numbers in neon green
- Same spacing as unordered

## Implementation

### CSS
```scss
ul, ol {
  padding-left: 1.5rem;
  margin: 1rem 0;

  li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
}

ul {
  list-style: none;

  li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 1rem;

    &::before {
      content: '>';
      position: absolute;
      left: 0;
      color: var(--color-primary);
      font-family: var(--font-heading);
    }
  }
}

// Alternative using ::marker (simpler but less control)
// ul li::marker {
//   color: var(--color-primary);
// }

ol {
  li::marker {
    color: var(--color-primary);
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Unordered lists have neon green bullets/markers
- [ ] Ordered lists have neon green numbers
- [ ] Spacing between items is comfortable
- [ ] Nested lists work correctly
- [ ] Indentation is appropriate

# Task: Style Footer with Dark Theme

## What
Redesign the footer to match the hacker theme with dark surface background and muted text.

## Why
- Visual consistency with header
- Professional closure to pages
- Contains important links (LinkedIn, email)
- Should be subtle, not attention-grabbing

## Design Specification

### Visual
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔│
│            © 2026 Milosz Czajkowski                     │
│       Built with Jekyll • Hosted on GitHub Pages        │
│               LinkedIn • Email                          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Background: #161b22 (surface)
Text: #8b949e (muted)
Links: #00ffff (cyan) → #ff00ff (magenta) on hover
Border: #30363d (1px top)
```

### Content
- Copyright with dynamic year
- Tech credits (Jekyll + GitHub Pages)
- Social links (LinkedIn, Email)

## Implementation

### CSS
```scss
.site-footer {
  background-color: var(--bg-surface);
  border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  padding: 2rem 0;
  margin-top: 3rem;
  text-align: center;

  p {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin: 0.5rem 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  a {
    color: var(--color-secondary);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color var(--transition-fast);

    &:hover {
      color: var(--color-hover);
    }
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Footer has dark surface background
- [ ] Top border separates from content
- [ ] Text is muted gray
- [ ] Links are cyan with magenta hover
- [ ] Content is centered
- [ ] Spacing feels balanced

# Task: Define CSS Custom Properties

## What
Create the CSS variable system that defines the entire color palette and typography references.

## Why
- Single source of truth for all colors
- Easy to tweak and maintain
- Enables potential future theming
- Industry best practice for design systems

## Implementation

### In assets/css/style.scss
```scss
---
---

// CSS Custom Properties (must be before @import to override Minima)
:root {
  // Backgrounds
  --bg-primary: #0d1117;
  --bg-surface: #161b22;

  // Accent colors
  --color-primary: #39ff14;    // Neon green
  --color-secondary: #00ffff;  // Cyan
  --color-hover: #ff00ff;      // Magenta
  --color-warning: #ff8c00;    // Orange

  // Text colors
  --text-primary: #c9d1d9;
  --text-muted: #8b949e;

  // Borders
  --border-color: #30363d;

  // Typography
  --font-heading: 'Share Tech Mono', monospace;
  --font-body: 'Fira Code', monospace;

  // Transitions
  --transition-fast: 0.2s ease;
  --transition-normal: 0.3s ease;

  // Spacing
  --content-max-width: 800px;
  --spacing-unit: 1rem;
}

@import "minima";

// Base overrides
html {
  background-color: var(--bg-primary);
}

body {
  background-color: var(--bg-primary);
  color: var(--text-primary);
  font-family: var(--font-body);
  line-height: 1.6;
}
```

## Color Reference Table
| Variable | Hex | Visual |
|----------|-----|--------|
| --bg-primary | #0d1117 | Dark charcoal (GitHub dark) |
| --bg-surface | #161b22 | Slightly lighter dark |
| --color-primary | #39ff14 | Neon green (Matrix-style) |
| --color-secondary | #00ffff | Cyan (terminal accent) |
| --color-hover | #ff00ff | Magenta (synthwave) |
| --color-warning | #ff8c00 | Orange (badges) |
| --text-primary | #c9d1d9 | Light gray (readable) |
| --text-muted | #8b949e | Medium gray (secondary) |
| --border-color | #30363d | Dark gray (subtle) |

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All variables defined in :root
- [ ] Body background is dark
- [ ] Body text is light gray
- [ ] Variables use semantic names
- [ ] Comments explain each variable group

# Epic: Theme Foundation - Colors & Typography

## Overview
Establish the core CSS foundation that all other styling builds upon. This includes CSS custom properties (variables) for the color palette and typography setup with Google Fonts.

## Why This Comes First
- All component styling references these variables
- Changing colors later only requires editing variables
- Typography must load before content renders
- Foundation errors cascade to everything else

## Technical Approach

### CSS Custom Properties
Define in `:root` for global access:
```css
:root {
  /* Backgrounds */
  --bg-primary: #0d1117;
  --bg-surface: #161b22;

  /* Accents */
  --color-primary: #39ff14;    /* Neon green */
  --color-secondary: #00ffff;  /* Cyan */
  --color-hover: #ff00ff;      /* Magenta */
  --color-warning: #ff8c00;    /* Orange */

  /* Text */
  --text-primary: #c9d1d9;
  --text-muted: #8b949e;

  /* Borders */
  --border-color: #30363d;

  /* Typography */
  --font-heading: 'Share Tech Mono', monospace;
  --font-body: 'Fira Code', monospace;
}
```

### Google Fonts Integration
Add to default.html head:
```html
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Fira+Code:wght@400;500;600&family=Share+Tech+Mono&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
```

### Base Reset
```css
html, body {
  background-color: var(--bg-primary);
  color: var(--text-primary);
  font-family: var(--font-body);
}
```

## Files to Modify
- `_layouts/default.html` - Add font links
- `assets/css/style.scss` - Add variables and base styles

## Success Criteria
- [ ] CSS variables defined and accessible
- [ ] Fonts loading correctly
- [ ] Body background is dark (#0d1117)
- [ ] Body text is light gray (#c9d1d9)
- [ ] Monospace font applied throughout

## Blocks
All component styling tasks depend on this.

# Task: Add Blinking Cursor Animation

## What
Implement the classic terminal blinking cursor effect after the site title.

## Why
- Signature visual element of the theme
- Immediately communicates "terminal" aesthetic
- Classic hacker/developer feel
- Simple but effective

## Design Specification

### Visual
```
> Milosz Czajkowski_
                   ↑
            Blinking cursor (on/off every 0.5s)
```

### Animation Properties
- Type: Step animation (instant on/off, not fade)
- Interval: 1 second total (0.5s visible, 0.5s hidden)
- Character: Underscore `_`
- Color: Same as title (neon green)

## Implementation

### HTML (in header.html)
```html
<a class="site-title" href="{{ '/' | relative_url }}">
  <span class="prompt">&gt;</span> {{ site.title }}<span class="cursor">_</span>
</a>
```

### CSS
```scss
@keyframes blink {
  0%, 50% {
    opacity: 1;
  }
  50.01%, 100% {
    opacity: 0;
  }
}

.site-title .cursor {
  animation: blink 1s step-end infinite;
}

// Respect reduced motion preference
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .site-title .cursor {
    animation: none;
    opacity: 1; // Show static cursor
  }
}
```

## Accessibility
- Blinking can be distracting for some users
- prefers-reduced-motion stops animation
- Cursor remains visible but static

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Cursor blinks after site title
- [ ] Blink is step-based (not fade)
- [ ] ~1 second cycle
- [ ] Reduced motion disables animation
- [ ] Cursor is visible when animation disabled

# Task: Style Headings

## What
Apply the hacker theme to all heading levels with neon green H1s and cyan H2s.

## Why
- Headings establish visual hierarchy
- Neon green H1s are the signature "pop" element
- Cyan H2s provide secondary level distinction
- Consistent heading styles across all pages

## Design Specification

### H1 (Page Titles)
- Color: Neon green (#39ff14)
- Font: Share Tech Mono
- Optional prefix: `> ` or `# `
- Subtle text-shadow glow effect
- Size: ~2rem

### H2 (Section Headings)
- Color: Cyan (#00ffff)
- Font: Share Tech Mono
- Clean, no prefix
- Size: ~1.5rem

### H3+ (Sub-sections)
- Color: Light gray (text-primary)
- Font: Share Tech Mono
- Smaller sizes

## Implementation

### CSS
```scss
h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6 {
  font-family: var(--font-heading);
  font-weight: 400;
  line-height: 1.3;
  margin-top: 2rem;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}

h1 {
  color: var(--color-primary);
  font-size: 2rem;
  text-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(57, 255, 20, 0.3);

  // Optional: Add prompt prefix via CSS
  // &::before { content: '> '; opacity: 0.7; }
}

h2 {
  color: var(--color-secondary);
  font-size: 1.5rem;
}

h3 {
  color: var(--text-primary);
  font-size: 1.25rem;
}

h4, h5, h6 {
  color: var(--text-muted);
  font-size: 1rem;
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] H1 is neon green with subtle glow
- [ ] H2 is cyan
- [ ] All headings use Share Tech Mono
- [ ] Heading hierarchy is clear
- [ ] Spacing above/below feels right

# Task: Implement Mobile-First Responsive Layout

## What
Create the core responsive framework with mobile-first breakpoints.

## Why
- Majority of web traffic is mobile
- Mobile-first ensures core experience works everywhere
- Progressive enhancement is best practice
- Prevents mobile afterthought problems

## Breakpoint Strategy

### Mobile (default)
```scss
// Base styles - no media query
.wrapper {
  padding: 0 1rem;
  max-width: 100%;
}
```

### Tablet (768px+)
```scss
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .wrapper {
    padding: 0 2rem;
  }
}
```

### Desktop (1024px+)
```scss
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .wrapper {
    max-width: var(--content-max-width);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 0 2rem;
  }
}
```

## Implementation

### CSS Variables
```scss
:root {
  --content-max-width: 800px;
  --spacing-mobile: 1rem;
  --spacing-desktop: 2rem;
}
```

### Base Layout
```scss
.page-content {
  padding: var(--spacing-mobile);

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    padding: var(--spacing-desktop);
  }
}

.wrapper {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: var(--content-max-width);
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 0 var(--spacing-mobile);

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    padding: 0 var(--spacing-desktop);
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Base styles work on 320px screens
- [ ] Tablet breakpoint adds comfort
- [ ] Desktop constrains content width
- [ ] Padding scales appropriately
- [ ] No horizontal overflow

# Task: Make Header Responsive

## What
Ensure the header layout adapts from mobile to desktop seamlessly.

## Why
- Header is visible on every page
- Must work on all screen sizes
- Navigation must remain usable
- Touch targets must be adequate

## Layout Specifications

### Mobile (< 768px)
```
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│    > Milosz Czajkowski_     │  <- Centered
│  Services About Blog Contact │  <- Centered, wrapped
└─────────────────────────────┘
```

### Desktop (>= 768px)
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ > Milosz Czajkowski_            Services About Blog Contact │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Implementation

### CSS
```scss
.site-header {
  .wrapper {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;

    @media (min-width: 768px) {
      flex-direction: row;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: center;
    }
  }
}

.site-nav {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  justify-content: center;
  gap: 0.5rem 1rem;

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    gap: 1.5rem;
  }
}

.nav-link {
  padding: 0.5rem; // Touch target

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    padding: 0;
  }
}
```

## Considerations
- Nav links need adequate tap targets on mobile
- Consider font size reduction on very small screens
- Test with long navigation text

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Header stacks on mobile
- [ ] Header is horizontal on desktop
- [ ] Navigation links are tappable on mobile
- [ ] No overflow issues
- [ ] Smooth transition at breakpoint

# Task: Create Main Stylesheet

## What
Create the Sass stylesheet that extends Minima theme.

## Why
- Jekyll requires front matter to process .scss files
- Imports Minima base for consistent styling
- Provides hook for custom overrides
- Single file manages all custom CSS

## File Content
```scss
---
---

@import "minima";

// Custom overrides below
// Keep minimal for MVP - only add if default minima is insufficient
```

## Key Points
1. **Empty front matter (---)**: Required for Jekyll to process Sass
2. **@import "minima"**: Pulls in all Minima theme styles
3. **Comments**: Placeholder for future customization

## Why Minimal CSS for MVP
- Minima is already responsive and professional
- Over-customizing delays shipping
- Can iterate on design post-launch
- Each custom rule is maintenance debt

## Future Customization Examples (NOT for MVP)
```scss
// Example: Adjust primary color
// $brand-color: #2a7ae2;

// Example: Custom header styling
// .site-header { 
//   border-bottom: 2px solid $brand-color; 
// }
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] File exists at assets/css/style.scss
- [ ] Has empty front matter
- [ ] Imports minima
- [ ] Site styling works after build
- [ ] No Sass compilation errors

## Parent Epic
[EPIC] Assets & Static Files

# Task: Style Buttons and CTAs

## What
Create a distinctive button style with ghost/outline default and filled hover state.

## Why
- CTAs drive conversions (contact, booking)
- Must stand out but fit the theme
- Ghost style fits hacker aesthetic
- Hover feedback confirms interactivity

## Design Specification

### Primary Button (Neon Green)
```
Default:  [ VIEW SERVICES ]  - transparent bg, green border, green text
Hover:    [ VIEW SERVICES ]  - green bg, dark text
```

### Secondary Button (Cyan)
```
Default:  [ LEARN MORE ]  - transparent bg, cyan border, cyan text
Hover:    [ LEARN MORE ]  - cyan bg, dark text
```

### Visual Properties
- Border: 2px solid
- Padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem
- Text: Uppercase, letter-spacing: 0.1em
- Font: Share Tech Mono
- Border-radius: 0 (sharp corners for tech feel)

## Implementation

### CSS
```scss
.btn, 
a.btn,
button {
  display: inline-block;
  font-family: var(--font-heading);
  font-size: 0.9rem;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem;
  border: 2px solid var(--color-primary);
  background: transparent;
  color: var(--color-primary);
  text-decoration: none;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: all var(--transition-fast);

  &:hover,
  &:focus {
    background-color: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--bg-primary);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
}

.btn-secondary {
  border-color: var(--color-secondary);
  color: var(--color-secondary);

  &:hover,
  &:focus {
    background-color: var(--color-secondary);
    color: var(--bg-primary);
  }
}
```

### HTML Usage
```html
<a href="/contact/" class="btn">Get in Touch</a>
<a href="/services/" class="btn btn-secondary">View Services</a>
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Buttons have ghost/outline style by default
- [ ] Hover fills the button with color
- [ ] Text inverts to dark on hover
- [ ] Uppercase with letter-spacing
- [ ] Sharp corners (no border-radius)
- [ ] Both primary and secondary variants work

# Task: Style Header with Terminal Prompt

## What
Redesign the site header to feature a terminal prompt effect with the site title and styled navigation.

## Why
- First thing visitors see
- Sets the tone for the entire hacker aesthetic
- Terminal prompt is the signature visual element
- Navigation must be clear and usable

## Design Specification

### Visual
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ > Milosz Czajkowski_                Services About Blog Contact │
│▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁▁│
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Background: #161b22 (surface)
Title: #39ff14 (neon green)
Nav links: #00ffff (cyan) → #ff00ff (magenta) on hover
Border: #30363d (1px bottom)
```

### Title Treatment
- Prefix: `> ` (terminal prompt)
- Suffix: `_` (cursor, animated blink)
- Font: Share Tech Mono
- Color: Neon green (#39ff14)

### Navigation
- Horizontal layout (desktop)
- Cyan links, no underline
- Magenta on hover with underline
- Smooth transition

## Implementation

### _includes/header.html
```html
<header class="site-header">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <a class="site-title" href="{{ '/' | relative_url }}">
      <span class="prompt">&gt;</span> {{ site.title }}<span class="cursor">_</span>
    </a>
    <nav class="site-nav">
      {% for item in site.data.navigation.main %}
        <a class="nav-link" href="{{ item.url | relative_url }}">{{ item.title }}</a>
      {% endfor %}
    </nav>
  </div>
</header>
```

### CSS
```scss
.site-header {
  background-color: var(--bg-surface);
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  padding: 1rem 0;
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 100;
}

.site-title {
  font-family: var(--font-heading);
  color: var(--color-primary);
  font-size: 1.25rem;
  text-decoration: none;

  .prompt { opacity: 0.7; }

  .cursor {
    animation: blink 1s step-end infinite;
  }
}

.nav-link {
  color: var(--color-secondary);
  text-decoration: none;
  margin-left: 1.5rem;
  transition: color var(--transition-fast);

  &:hover {
    color: var(--color-hover);
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Header has dark surface background
- [ ] Title shows `> Milosz Czajkowski_` format
- [ ] Cursor blinks
- [ ] Nav links are cyan
- [ ] Nav links turn magenta on hover
- [ ] Bottom border visible
- [ ] Sticky behavior works

# Task: Add Smooth Hover Transitions

## What
Ensure all interactive elements have smooth color transitions on hover.

## Why
- Instant color changes feel jarring
- Smooth transitions feel polished
- Consistent timing across all elements
- Professional user experience

## Elements to Apply

### Links
```scss
a {
  transition: color 0.2s ease, text-decoration 0.2s ease;
}
```

### Buttons
```scss
.btn {
  transition: all 0.2s ease;
  // Covers background, color, border
}
```

### Navigation Links
```scss
.nav-link {
  transition: color 0.2s ease;
}
```

## Implementation

### CSS Variables for Consistency
```scss
:root {
  --transition-fast: 0.2s ease;
  --transition-normal: 0.3s ease;
}
```

### Apply Globally
```scss
a, button, .btn, input, textarea {
  transition: color var(--transition-fast),
              background-color var(--transition-fast),
              border-color var(--transition-fast);
}
```

## Considerations
- Don't transition layout properties (width, height, margin)
- Those can cause reflows and jank
- Stick to color, background, opacity, transform

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Link color changes smoothly
- [ ] Button hover effect is smooth
- [ ] Nav links have smooth transition
- [ ] No instant/jarring color changes
- [ ] ~0.2s duration feels right
